This seasonal occurrence of clinically severe malnutrition bears an in-
teresting relationship to the observed seasonal trends in biochemical indices
of nutriture. Plasma protein levels were lowest in the winter and autumn, the
periods marked by the most clinical malnutrition (see Figure 12 and Table 21).
A similar seasonal trend in hemoglobin values for the younger ages (less than
5 years), in MCHC, in serum carotene levels for the younger age groups, and in
vitamin A concentration for all groups (Figures 13-14 and Table 21) is evident.
old
Urinary thiamine excretion, despite its relatively high level, tended to
show similar seasonal lows in winter and autumn (Figure 15).
PREVALENCE
Urinary nitrogen excretions per gram of creatinine usually were highest in
the summer and spring, but the seasonal differences were not so striking as was
the generally low level of these excretions, obviously reflecting widespread
insufficiency of protein intake. Whether there is an inverse relationship be-
tween urinary nitrogen excretion and riboflavin excretion is not readily ap-
parent from the data (Figure 16), although there is some suggestion of such a

The evidence for a significant amount of severe protein-Calorie malnutri-
tion of all three types, marasmus, kwashiorkor and prekwashiorkor, for a sea-
sonal variation in the occurrence of these clinically manifest syndromes, for
similar seasonal variations in biochemical measures of nutriture, and the sea-
sonal pattern of diarrheal diseases and respiratory infections point to an inter-
play between nutritional status and diarrheal and infectious diseases. This
interplay is not only the direct effect of one of these conditions upon the other,
but importantly at times may relate to changes in the feeding of the child which
are made by the mother in an effort to "treat" diarrhea or other illness. A com-
mon procedure invoked by the mother is further to restrict quantities of solid
foods and even of milk whenever diarrhea occurs. Concomitant anorexia may sim-
ilarly act to reduce the dietary intake and further aggravate the state of mal-
